{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2024-01-03","name":"John Bruley II","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"John Bruley II","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"John"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"Bruley"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Suffix","value":"II"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"alternateName":"John de Bruley II","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1305–1372","fullLifespan":"Abt 1305–Bef 1372","birthDate":"+1305","birthPlace":{"address":"Waterstoke, Oxfordshire, England","geo":{"latitude":51.746,"longitude":-1.073,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathPlace":{"address":"Oxfordshire, England","geo":{"latitude":51.85739,"longitude":-1.29353,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"«b»Biography«/b»\nJohn Bruley was lord of the manor in 1316 and 1327. The date of his death is uncertain and his heir according to the herald's pedigree was John. He appears to have been succeeded at Waterstock, however, by a Thomas Bruley: in 1346 John Bruley was returned as holding the manor, sometime held by Thomas Bruley. It is likely that this Thomas was John Bruley's younger brother whom he had presented to the rectory, and that he acted as guardian to John II when he was a minor. John II, who was probably the husband of Bona Fitzellis and collector of the subsidy in Oxfordshire in 1350, may have been dead by 1361, when Thomas Bruley is said to have presented a certain Thomas atte Fortheye on the death of the rector Thomas Bruley, but it is more probable that John was still patron and that the appearance of 'Thomas' as patron is the result of a scribal error. By 1372 at all events John II was dead and his heir John III was a minor. The boy may never have succeeded, as in 1380 Waterstock was in the possession of William and Agnes Bruley. The suggestion that William Bruley was John's son is hardly possible and he was more probably a cousin, a descendant of Henry, the youngest brother of John (I) Bruley. There seems little doubt that his wife Agnes was his cousin and the descendant of William Bruley, John I's eldest brother or nephew. The fine made by Agnes and William in 1380 implies that Agnes had a claim to Waterstock in her own right: they settled the pro perty first on the heirs of their bodies; secondly on the heirs of Agnes by a second marriage; and thirdly on the collateral heirs of William.","sourceList":[{"title":"Our royal, titled, noble and commoner ancestors","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://our-royal-titled-noble-and-commoner-ancestors.com/p1089.htm#i32698","sourceUri":"3BCR-3PD"},{"title":"Legacy NFS Source: John de Bruley - ","sourceType":"LEGACY","sourceUri":"M9G4-7G5"}],"events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1305","date":"Abt 1305","place":"Waterstoke, Oxfordshire, England"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1327","date":"1327","place":"Waterstoke, Oxfordshire, England","age":"22","id":"G61Z-VJR"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1340","date":"19 February 1340","place":"Waterstock, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","age":"35","id":"K2SF-V4R"},{"name":"Marriage","sources":"0","year":"1346","date":"Abt 1346","place":"England, UK","type":"Spousal","age":"41","id":"GD3P-38S"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1348","date":"1348","place":"Waterstoke, Oxfordshire, England","age":"43","id":"G7BQ-2QB"},{"name":"Death","sources":"0","year":"1372","date":"Bef 1372","place":"Oxfordshire, England","age":"66"},{"name":"Marriage","sources":"0","year":"1304","date":"1304","place":"Waterstoke, Oxfordshire, England","type":"Parental"}],"parent":[{"name":"John Bruley","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1272–1327","birthDate":"A+1272","deathDate":"+1327","age":55,"@type":"Person","identifier":"G61Z-VJR","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/G61Z-VJR/john-bruley-1272-1327","published":true},{"name":"Francis Bruley","gender":"Female","lifespan":"1276–1340","birthDate":"+1276-04-02","deathDate":"+1340-02-19","age